{"title_page": "Histone-modifying enzymes", "text_new": "[[Image:NucleosomeKG.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Histone]]-Modifying Enzymes, the sites for modification are marked in color.]]\n\nThe packaging of the [[eukaryotic]] [[genome]] into highly condensed [[chromatin]] makes it inaccessible to the factors required for gene [[Transcription (genetics)|transcription]], DNA replication, [[genetic recombination|recombination]] and repair. [[Eukaryotes]] have developed intricate mechanisms to overcome this repressive barrier imposed by the [[chromatin]]. The nucleosome is composed of an octamer of the four core [[histone]]s (H3, H4, H2A, H2B) around which 146 base pairs of DNA are wrapped. Several distinct classes of [[enzyme]] can modify [[histone]]s at multiple sites.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kouzarides T |title=Chromatin modifications and their function |journal=Cell |volume=128 |issue=4 |pages=693\u2013705 |date=February 2007 |pmid=17320507 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2007.02.005 }}</ref> The figure on the right enlists those histone-modifying enzymes whose specificity has been determined. There are at least eight distinct types of modifications found on [[histones]] (see the legend box on the top left of the figure). [[Enzyme]]s have been identified for [[acetylation]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sterner DE, Berger SL |title=Acetylation of histones and transcription-related factors |journal=Microbiol. Mol. Biol. Rev. |volume=64 |issue=2 |pages=435\u201359 |date=June 2000 |pmid=10839822 |pmc=98999 |doi=10.1128/MMBR.64.2.435-459.2000}}</ref>\n[[methylation]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zhang Y, Reinberg D |title=Transcription regulation by histone methylation: interplay between different covalent modifications of the core histone tails |journal=Genes Dev. |volume=15  |pages=2343\u201360 |year=2001 |doi=10.1101/gad.927301 |pmid=11562345 |issue=18|doi-access=free }}</ref> [[demethylation]],<ref name=\"pmid17342184\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Klose RJ, Zhang Y |title=Regulation of histone methylation by demethylimination and demethylation |journal=Nat. Rev. Mol. Cell Biol. |volume=8 |issue=4 |pages=307\u201318 |year=2007 |pmid=17342184 |doi=10.1038/nrm2143}}</ref> [[phosphorylation]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nowak SJ, Corces VG |title=Phosphorylation of histone H3: a balancing act between chromosome condensation and transcriptional activation |journal=Trends Genet. |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=214\u201320 |date=April 2004 |pmid=15041176 |doi=10.1016/j.tig.2004.02.007 }}</ref> \n[[ubiquitination]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Shilatifard A |title=Chromatin modifications by methylation and ubiquitination: implications in the regulation of gene expression |journal=Annu. Rev. Biochem. |volume=75 |pages=243\u201369 |year=2006 |pmid=16756492 |doi=10.1146/annurev.biochem.75.103004.142422 }}</ref> [[sumoylation]],<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Nathan D, Ingvarsdottir K, Sterner DE, etal |title=Histone sumoylation is a negative regulator in Saccharomyces cerevisiae and shows dynamic interplay with positive-acting histone modifications |journal=Genes Dev. |volume=20 |issue=8 |pages=966\u201376 |date=April 2006 |pmid=16598039 |pmc=1472304 |doi=10.1101/gad.1404206 }}</ref>\n[[ADP-ribosylation]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hassa PO, Haenni SS, Elser M, Hottiger MO |title=Nuclear ADP-ribosylation reactions in mammalian cells: where are we today and where are we going? |journal=Microbiol. Mol. Biol. Rev. |volume=70 |issue=3 |pages=789\u2013829 |date=September 2006 |pmid=16959969 |pmc=1594587 |doi=10.1128/MMBR.00040-05 }}</ref> \n[[deimination]],<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Cuthbert GL, Daujat S, Snowden AW, etal |title=Histone deimination antagonizes arginine methylation |journal=Cell |volume=118 |issue=5 |pages=545\u201353 |date=September 2004 |pmid=15339660 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2004.08.020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Wang Y, Wysocka J, Sayegh J, etal |title=Human PAD4 regulates histone arginine methylation levels via demethylimination |journal=Science |volume=306 |issue=5694 |pages=279\u201383 |date=October 2004 |pmid=15345777 |doi=10.1126/science.1101400 |bibcode=2004Sci...306..279W }}</ref> and \n[[proline isomerization]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nelson CJ, Santos-Rosa H, Kouzarides T |title=Proline isomerization of histone H3 regulates lysine methylation and gene expression |journal=Cell |volume=126 |issue=5 |pages=905\u201316 |date=September 2006 |pmid=16959570 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2006.07.026 }}</ref> For a detailed example of histone modifications in transcription regulation see [[RNA polymerase control by chromatin structure]] and table \"[[Histone#Histone modifications|Examples of histone modifications in transcriptional regulation]]\". Different physiological changes (e.g. deficiency of vitamin B12, etc.) are known to be associated with behavioural changes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ghosh|first=Shampa|last2=Sinha|first2=Jitendra Kumar|last3=Khandelwal|first3=Nitin|last4=Chakravarty|first4=Sumana|last5=Kumar|first5=Arvind|last6=Raghunath|first6=Manchala|date=2018-11-25|title=Increased stress and altered expression of histone modifying enzymes in brain are associated with aberrant behaviour in vitamin B12 deficient female mice|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/1028415X.2018.1548676|journal=Nutritional Neuroscience|volume=0|issue=0|pages=1\u201310|doi=10.1080/1028415X.2018.1548676|issn=1028-415X|pmid=30474509}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saraswathy|first=Kallur Nava|last2=Ansari|first2=Shagufta Naaz|last3=Kaur|first3=Gurjinder|last4=Joshi|first4=Pooran Chand|last5=Chandel|first5=Shivani|date=2019-04|title=Association of vitamin B12 mediated hyperhomocysteinemia with depression and anxiety disorder: A cross-sectional study among Bhil indigenous population of India|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.clnesp.2019.01.009|journal=Clinical Nutrition ESPEN|volume=30|pages=199\u2013203|doi=10.1016/j.clnesp.2019.01.009|issn=2405-4577}}</ref> In a 2009 review article<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marmorstein|first=Ronen|last2=Trievel|first2=Raymond C.|date=2009-1|title=Histone Modifying Enzymes: Structures, Mechanisms, and Specificities|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4059211/|journal=Biochimica et biophysica acta|volume=1789|issue=1|pages=58\u201368|doi=10.1016/j.bbagrm.2008.07.009|issn=0006-3002|pmc=4059211|pmid=18722564}}</ref>, authors have summarized different studies of the [[Histone acetyltransferase|histone acetyltransferases]] (HATs) p300 and Rtt109 (KAT11), and the histone lysine [[Demethylase|demethylases]] (HDMs) LSD1 (KDM1) and JMJD2A (KDM4A). Additionally, recent evidences show the importance of HDACs in regulation of lipid metabolism and other metabolic pathways playing role in the pathophysiology of metabolic disorders<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23095054/|title=Linking Epigenetics to Lipid Metabolism: Focus on Histone Deacetylases|last=A|first=Ferrari|last2=E|first2=Fiorino|date=2012 Nov|website=Molecular membrane biology|language=en|pmid=23095054|access-date=2020-04-17|last3=M|first3=Giudici|last4=F|first4=Gilardi|last5=A|first5=Galmozzi|last6=N|first6=Mitro|last7=G|first7=Cermenati|last8=C|first8=Godio|last9=D|first9=Caruso}}</ref>. \n\n==See also==\n* [[Histone deacetylase]]s\n* [[Histone methyltransferase]]\n* [[Histone acetyltransferase]]\n* [[Nucleosome]]\n* [[Chromatin]]\n* [[PRMT4 pathway]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Histone-Modifying Enzymes}}\n[[Category:Epigenetics]]\n[[Category:Proteins]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:NucleosomeKG.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Histone]]-Modifying Enzymes, the sites for modification are marked in color.]]\n\nThe packaging of the [[eukaryotic]] [[genome]] into highly condensed [[chromatin]] makes it inaccessible to the factors required for gene [[Transcription (genetics)|transcription]], DNA replication, [[genetic recombination|recombination]] and repair. [[Eukaryotes]] have developed intricate mechanisms to overcome this repressive barrier imposed by the [[chromatin]]. The nucleosome is composed of an octamer of the four core [[histone]]s (H3, H4, H2A, H2B) around which 146 base pairs of DNA are wrapped. Several distinct classes of [[enzyme]] can modify [[histone]]s at multiple sites.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kouzarides T |title=Chromatin modifications and their function |journal=Cell |volume=128 |issue=4 |pages=693\u2013705 |date=February 2007 |pmid=17320507 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2007.02.005 }}</ref> The figure on the right enlists those histone-modifying enzymes whose specificity has been determined. There are at least eight distinct types of modifications found on [[histones]] (see the legend box on the top left of the figure). [[Enzyme]]s have been identified for [[acetylation]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sterner DE, Berger SL |title=Acetylation of histones and transcription-related factors |journal=Microbiol. Mol. Biol. Rev. |volume=64 |issue=2 |pages=435\u201359 |date=June 2000 |pmid=10839822 |pmc=98999 |doi=10.1128/MMBR.64.2.435-459.2000}}</ref>\n[[methylation]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zhang Y, Reinberg D |title=Transcription regulation by histone methylation: interplay between different covalent modifications of the core histone tails |journal=Genes Dev. |volume=15  |pages=2343\u201360 |year=2001 |doi=10.1101/gad.927301 |pmid=11562345 |issue=18|doi-access=free }}</ref> [[demethylation]],<ref name=\"pmid17342184\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Klose RJ, Zhang Y |title=Regulation of histone methylation by demethylimination and demethylation |journal=Nat. Rev. Mol. Cell Biol. |volume=8 |issue=4 |pages=307\u201318 |year=2007 |pmid=17342184 |doi=10.1038/nrm2143}}</ref> [[phosphorylation]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nowak SJ, Corces VG |title=Phosphorylation of histone H3: a balancing act between chromosome condensation and transcriptional activation |journal=Trends Genet. |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=214\u201320 |date=April 2004 |pmid=15041176 |doi=10.1016/j.tig.2004.02.007 }}</ref> \n[[ubiquitination]],<ref>{{cite journal |