{"title_page": "Western Front demarcation stones", "text_new": "[[File:Stuivekenskerke - Demarcatiepaal nr 11.jpg|thumb|Side view of a Belgian Army-style demarcation stone in [[Stuivekenskerke]]]]\n'''Western Front demarcation stones''' also known as '''''Bornes du Front''''' (Front terminals) and '''''Bornes Vauthier''''' (Vauthier terminals) are monuments erected in France and Belgium to mark the limit of the German advance during the [[First World War]].  The stones were the idea of sculptor [[Paul Moreau-Vauthier]], a veteran of the war, and were erected between 1921 and 1930.  The total number of stones erected is unclear but it is thought that there were 118 official stones, of which 93 survive.  The stones identify the army (Belgian, British or French) that held that sector in 1918 and are engraved with the text \"Here the invader was brought to a standstill 1918\" in English, Flemish and French.  \n\n== History ==\n[[File:CT- inauguration de la borne marquant l'arr\u00eat de la marche allemande.jpg|thumb|Inauguration of the stone at [[Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry]], 10 November 1921]]\nThe stones mark the of a line of the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in 1918 at the start of the Allied [[Hundred Days Offensive]], and thus mark [[Spring Offensive|the limit of the German advance]] into French and Belgian territory.<ref name=cooksey/>  The idea came from sculptor [[Paul Moreau-Vauthier]] who had served as a machine gunner in the French Army during the war and had been severely wounded at the [[Battle of Verdun]].  Vauthier presented the idea  at the Salon des Artistes Decorateurs in 1919.<ref name=holt>{{cite book |last1=Holt |first1=Major |last2=Holt |first2=Mrs Valmai |title=Major & Mrs Holt's Battlefield Guide to Ypres Salient and Passchendaele |date=2012 |publisher=Pen and Sword |isbn=978-0-85052-551-9 |page=119 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6PVsBQAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  The idea received the support of the [[Touring club de France]] and the [[Touring Club Belgium]] who arranged public subscriptions.<ref name=homsher>{{cite book |last1=Homsher |first1=David C. |title=American Battlefields of World War 1, Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry--then and Now: Enter the Yanks as told in the actual words of the soldiers |date=2006 |publisher=Battleground Productions |isbn=978-0-9702443-0-7 |page=258 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MfSM14o6uqgC |language=en}}</ref>  The original intention had been to erect a monument at every kilometre along the {{convert|960|km|mi}} long [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] but this was later scaled back.<ref name=homsher/><ref name=cooksey>{{cite book |last1=Cooksey |first1=Jon |last2=Murland |first2=Jerry |title=Battle Lines Ypres: Nieuwpoort to Ploegsteert |date=2013 |publisher=Casemate Publishers |isbn=978-1-78303-404-8 |page=393 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=k7XNDwAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  Sources vary on the number erected, giving a range of 119 to 280 stones, but it is thought that 119 were erected, of which 118 were official stones placed on the frontline.<ref name=holt/><ref name=homsher/>  It is though that 118 stones were erected between 1921 and 1930, 22 in Belgium and 96 in France.<ref name=cooksey/>\n\nThe stones were placed at locations selected by Marshal Petain and his staff and often occupy prominent positions such as roadsides.<ref name=holt/><ref name=homsher/>  They run from the North Sea coast of Belgium to the [[Vosges]] region of France.<ref name=holt/>  There are some anomalies such as the stone at Villers-Bretonneux which lies to the east of the town.  The town was actually occupied by the Germans during the 1918 [[Second Battle of Villers-Bretonneux]] but becuase the occupation was brief, a mere 24 hours, it was not considered when the stone was sited.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pedersen |first1=Peter |title=ANZACS on the Western Front: The Australian War Memorial Battlefield Guide |date=2012 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-1-118-23832-5 |page=463 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4w8Fi73sSIsC |language=en}}</ref>  Similarly a stone in the Somme region near [[H\u00e9buterne]] is positioned some {{convert|0.75|mi|km}} east of the actual limit of the German advance.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Middlebrook |first1=Martin |title=The Somme Battlefields: A Comprehensive Guide from Cr\u00e9cy to the Two World Wars |date=1991 |publisher=Viking |isbn=978-0-670-83083-1 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b1QfAAAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Fort de la pompelle 029.JPG|thumb|Front view of a French Army-style demarcation stone at the [[Fort de la Pompelle]]]]\nThe monuments were carved by stone mason [[L\u00e9on Telle]] from Alsace [[pink granite]].  They are {{convert|1|m|ft}} high and square in section.<ref name=holt/>  The top of the stone is carved with the helmet of the army that held that section of the line in 1918, with appropriate identifying badges.<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal of the Royal United Services Institution |date=1922 |publisher=W. Mitchell and Son |page=571 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pMJMAAAAYAAJ |language=en}}</ref><ref name=holt/>  Thus for Belgian and French sectors an [[Adrian helmet]] is depicted and for the British sector a [[Brodie helmet]] is used, in each case set upon a [[laurel wreath]].<ref name=holt/>  The front of the stone shows the name of the locality, the sides depict the typical infantryman's equipment of gas mask and water bottle and a [[hand grenade]] , with emerging [[palm branch]], is shown at each corner.<ref name=homsher/><ref name=holt/>  The front and two sides are engraved with the text \"Here the invader was brought to a standstill 1918\" in English, Flemish and French.  This was a change from Vauthier's original and more visceral text: \"Here the thrust of the barbarian was broken\". <ref name=holt/>\n\n== Today ==\nDuring the [[Second World War]] 24 of the monuments were destroyed and, as of 2013, only 93 survive anywhere - 12 of these in the [[Ypres Salient]].<ref name=cooksey/><ref name=holt/>  Some of the remaining monuments are in a poor condition.<ref name=cooksey/>\n\nIn February 2019 a new monument was erected at [[Morbecque]], in the Vauthier-style but in a white-coloured stone, to mark the location of the headquarters of the British [[Third Army (United Kingdom)|Third Army]].  The stone is surmounted with the Brodie helmet on a laurel wreath but does not show the standard text.  It is instead engraved with the names of the first and last British soliders to die in action and the English text \"Here fought the valiant British soldiers\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Morbecque - Une st\u00e8le en m\u00e9moire de l\u2019arm\u00e9e britannique inaugur\u00e9e samedi |url=https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/544468/article/2019-02-28/une-stele-en-memoire-de-l-armee-britannique-inauguree-samedi |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=La Voix du Nord |date=28 February 2019 |language=fr}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|World War I demarcation stones}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:World War I memorials in France]]\n[[Category:World War I memorials in Belgium]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Stuivekenskerke - Demarcatiepaal nr 11.jpg|thumb|Side view of a Belgian Army-style demarcation stone in [[Stuivekenskerke]]]]\n'''Western Front demarcation stones''' also known as '''''Bornes du Front''''' (Front terminals) and '''''Bornes Vauthier''''' (Vauthier terminals) are monuments erected in France and Belgium to mark the limit of the German advance during the [[First World War]].  The stones were the idea of sculptor [[Paul Moreau-Vauthier]], a veteran of the war, and were erected between 1921 and 1930.  The total number of stones erected is unclear but it is thought that there were 118 official stones, of which 93 survive.  The stones identify the army (Belgian, British or French) that held that sector in 1918 and are engraved with the text \"Here the invader was brought to a standstill 1918\" in English, Flemish and French.  \n\n== History ==\n[[File:CT- inauguration de la borne marquant l'arr\u00eat de la marche allemande.jpg|thumb|Inauguration of the stone at [[Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry]], 10 November 1921]]\nThe stones mark the of a line of the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in 1918 at the start of the Allied [[Hundred Days Offensive]], and thus mark [[Spring Offensive|the limit of the German advance]] into French and Belgian territory.<ref name=cooksey/>  The idea came from sculptor [[Paul Moreau-Vauthier]] who had served as a machine gunner in the French Army during the war and had been severely wounded at the [[Battle of Verdun]].  Vauthier presented the idea  at the Salon des Artistes Decorateurs in 1919.<ref name=holt>{{cite book |last1=Holt |first1=Major |last2=Holt |first2=Mrs Valmai |title=Major & Mrs Holt's Battlefield Guide to Ypres Salient and Passchendaele |date=2012 |publisher=Pen and Sword |isbn=978-0-85052-551-9 |page=119 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6PVsBQAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  The idea received the support of the [[Touring club de France]] and the [[Touring Club Belgium]] who arranged public subscriptions.<ref name=homsher>{{cite book |last1=Homsher |first1=David C. |title=American Battlefields of World War 1, Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry--then and Now: Enter the Yanks as told in the actual words of the soldiers |date=2006 |publisher=Battleground Productions |isbn=978-0-9702443-0-7 |page=258 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MfSM14o6uqgC |language=en}}</ref>  The original intention had been to erect a monument at every kilometre along the {{convert|960|km|mi}} long [[Western Front]] but this was later scaled back.<ref name=homsher/><ref name=cooksey>{{cite book |last1=Cooksey |first1=Jon |last2=Murland |first2=Jerry |title=Battle Lines Ypres: Nieuwpoort to Ploegsteert |date=2013 |publisher=Casemate Publishers |isbn=978-1-78303-404-8 |page=393 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=k7XNDwAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref>  Sources vary on the number erected, giving a range of 119 to 280 stones, but it is thought that 119 were erected, of which 118 were official stones placed on the frontline.<ref name=holt/><ref name=homsher/>  It is though that 118 stones were erected between 1921 and 1930, 22 in Belgium and 96 in France.<ref name=cooksey/>\n\nThe stones were placed at locations selected by Marshal Petain and his staff and often occupy prominent positions such as roadsides.<ref name=holt/><ref name=homsher/>  They run from the North Sea coast of Belgium to the [[Vosges]] region of France.<ref name=holt/>  There are some anomalies such as the stone at Villers-Bretonneux which lies to the east of the town.  The town was actually occupied by the Germans during the 1918 [[Second Battle of Villers-Bretonneux]] but becuase the occupation was brief, a mere 24 hours, it was not considered when the stone was sited.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pedersen |first1=Peter |title=ANZACS on the Western Front: The Australian War Memorial Battlefield Guide |date=2012 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-1-118-23832-5 |page=463 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4w8Fi73sSIsC |language=en}}</ref>  Similarly a stone in the Somme region near [[H\u00e9buterne]] is positioned some {{convert|0.75|mi|km}} east of the actual limit of the German advance.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Middlebrook |first1=Martin |title=The Somme Battlefields: A Comprehensive Guide from Cr\u00e9cy to the Two World Wars |date=1991 |publisher=Viking |isbn=978-0-670-83083-1 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b1QfAAAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Fort de la pompelle 029.JPG|thumb|Front view of a French Army-style demarcation stone at the [[Fort de la Pompelle]]]]\nThe monuments were carved by stone mason [[L\u00e9on Telle]] from Alsace [[pink granite]].  They are {{convert|1|m|ft}} high and square in section.<ref name=holt/>  The top of the stone is carved with the helmet of the army that held that section of the line in 1918, with appropriate identifying badges.<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal of the Royal United Services Institution |date=1922 |publisher=W. Mitchell and Son |page=571 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pMJMAAAAYAAJ |language=en}}</ref><ref name=holt/>  Thus for Belgian and French sectors an [[Adrian helmet]] is depicted and for the British sector a [[Brodie helmet]] is used, in each case set upon a [[laurel wreath]].<ref name=holt/>  The front of the stone shows the name of the locality, the sides depict the typical infantryman's equipment of gas mask and water bottle and a [[hand grenade]] , with emerging [[palm branch]], is shown at each corner.<ref name=homsher/><ref name=holt/>  The front and two sides are engraved with the text \"Here the invader was brought to a standstill 1918\" in English, Flemish and French.  This was a change from Vauthier's original and more visceral text: \"Here the thrust of the barbarian was broken\". <ref name=holt/>\n\n== Today ==\nDuring the [[Second World War]] 24 of the monuments were destroyed and, as of 2013, only 93 survive anywhere - 12 of these in the [[Ypres Salient]].<ref name=cooksey/><ref name=holt/>  Some of the remaining monuments are in a poor condition.<ref name=cooksey/>\n\nIn February 2019 a new monument was erected at [[Morbecque]], in the Vauthier-style but in a white-coloured stone, to mark the location of the headquarters of the British [[Third Army (United Kingdom)|Third Army]].  The stone is surmounted with the Brodie helmet on a laurel wreath but does not show the standard text.  It is instead engraved with the names of the first and last British soliders to die in action and the English text \"Here fought the valiant British soldiers\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Morbecque - Une st\u00e8le en m\u00e9moire de l\u2019arm\u00e9e britannique inaugur\u00e9e samedi |url=https://www.lavoixdunord.fr/544468/article/2019-02-28/une-stele-en-memoire-de-l-armee-britannique-inauguree-samedi |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=La Voix du Nord |date=28 February 2019 |language=fr}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|World War I demarcation stones}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:World War I memorials in France]]\n[[Category:World War I memorials in Belgium]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toWestern Front(link changed toWestern Front (World War I)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Front_demarcation_stones"}
{"title_page": "Nepiophilia", "text_new": "'''Nepiophilia''' (sometimes called \"'''infantophilia'''\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vartapetiance |first1=Anna |last2=Gillam |first2=Lee |title=\"Our Little Secret\": pinpointing potential predators |journal=Security Informatics |date=18 September 2014 |volume=3 |issue=1 |doi=10.1186/s13388-014-0003-7}}</ref>) is a strong, persistent sexual attraction by adults towards [[infants]] and [[toddlers]] (younger than 5 years old).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=Michael C. |title=Erratum to: The Puzzle of Male Chronophilias |journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior |date=12 July 2017 |volume=46 |issue=8 |pages=2525\u20132525 |doi=10.1007/s10508-017-1039-9}}</ref> Not to be confused with [[pedophilia]], which is an attraction to [[prepubescent]] children who are past the stage of infancy.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=MC |title=Pedophilia and sexual offending against children: Theory, assessment, and intervention. |doi=10.1037/11639-000}}</ref> There is some overlap between nepiophilia and pedophilia (ages 3-5), but, generally speaking, pedophiles are ''not'' attracted to infants and toddlers, while nepiophiles are ''only'' attracted to infants and toddlers (with exception for those who are \"non-exclusive\"). \n\nCurrently, the [[etiology]] of nepiophilia is unknown.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=Michael C. |title=Erratum to: The Puzzle of Male Chronophilias |journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior |date=12 July 2017 |volume=46 |issue=8 |pages=2525\u20132525 |doi=10.1007/s10508-017-1039-9}}</ref> It is not mentioned by the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] and is not scientifically considered [[pathological]] unless it causes the individual to engage in illegal sexual behavior with a child (see [[child sexual abuse]] and [[child pornography]]) or causes the individual to experience clinically-significant distress (see [[anxiety]] and [[depression]]), in which case it would meet the criteria to be diagnosed as [[pedophilic disorder]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=American Psychiatric Association |title=Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders : DSM-5. |isbn=9789386217967 |edition=Fifth}}</ref>\n\nNepiophilia is currently assumed to be the rarest [[chronophilia]], considerably less common than pedophilia, [[hebephilia]], or [[ephebophilia]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=Michael C. |title=Erratum to: The Puzzle of Male Chronophilias |journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior |date=12 July 2017 |volume=46 |issue=8 |pages=2525\u20132525 |doi=10.1007/s10508-017-1039-9}}</ref> Possibly as a result of its rarity, there appears to be less scientific research that is specific to nepiophilia. \n\nThe word nepiophilia is derived from the [[Greek roots]] \u03bd\u03ae\u03c0\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 (nepios), meaning \"infant,\" and \u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03af\u03b1 (philia), meaning \"love.\"\n", "text_old": "'''Nepiophilia''' (sometimes called \"'''infantophilia'''\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vartapetiance |first1=Anna |last2=Gillam |first2=Lee |title=\"Our Little Secret\": pinpointing potential predators |journal=Security Informatics |date=18 September 2014 |volume=3 |issue=1 |doi=10.1186/s13388-014-0003-7}}</ref>) is a strong, persistent sexual attraction by adults towards [[infants]] and [[toddlers]] (younger than 5 years old).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=Michael C. |title=Erratum to: The Puzzle of Male Chronophilias |journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior |date=12 July 2017 |volume=46 |issue=8 |pages=2525\u20132525 |doi=10.1007/s10508-017-1039-9}}</ref> Not to be confused with [[pedophilia]], which is an attraction to [[prepubescent]] children who are past the stage of infancy.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=MC |title=Pedophilia and sexual offending against children: Theory, assessment, and intervention. |doi=10.1037/11639-000}}</ref> There is some overlap between nepiophilia and pedophilia (ages 3-5), but, generally speaking, pedophiles are ''not'' attracted to infants and toddlers, while nepiophiles are ''only'' attracted to infants and toddlers (with exception for those who are \"non-exclusive\"). \n\nCurrently, the [[etiology]] of nepiophilia is unknown.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=Michael C. |title=Erratum to: The Puzzle of Male Chronophilias |journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior |date=12 July 2017 |volume=46 |issue=8 |pages=2525\u20132525 |doi=10.1007/s10508-017-1039-9}}</ref> It is not mentioned by the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] and is not scientifically considered [[pathological]] unless it causes the individual to engage in illegal sexual behavior with a child (see [[child sexual abuse]] and [[child pornography]]) or causes the individual to experience clinically-significant distress (see [[anxiety]] and [[depression]]), in which case it would meet the criteria to be diagnosed as [[pedophilic disorder]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=American Psychiatric Association |title=Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders : DSM-5. |isbn=9789386217967 |edition=Fifth}}</ref>\n\nNepiophilia is currently assumed to be the rarest [[chronophilia]], considerably less common than pedophilia, [[hebephilia]], or [[ephebophilia]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seto |first1=Michael C. |title=Erratum to: The Puzzle of Male Chronophilias |journal=Archives of Sexual Behavior |date=12 July 2017 |volume=46 |issue=8 |pages=2525\u20132525 |doi=10.1007/s10508-017-1039-9}}</ref> Possibly as a result of its rarity, there appears to be less scientific research that is specific to nepiophilia. \n\nThe word nepiophilia is derived from the Greek roots \u03bd\u03ae\u03c0\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 (nepios), meaning \"infant,\" and \u03c6\u03b9\u03bb\u03af\u03b1 (philia), meaning \"love.\"\n", "name_user": "Anon ducky", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a link to Wikipedia for the term \"Greek roots\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepiophilia"}
